  "why": "The paper focuses exclusively on the performance of the proposed testing framework, CrossASR++, in terms of the quantity of failures it can uncover compared to its predecessor. The experiments (RQ1 and RQ2) are designed to measure and demonstrate the efficiency and effectiveness of the tool's new features (e.g., extensibility, dynamic chunking, advanced estimators) in increasing the number of discovered failed test cases. The paper reports the total counts of failures for different Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) systems but provides no analysis of the failures themselves. It does not investigate the properties of the failure-inducing inputs, nor does it attempt to link the failures to statistical patterns (e.g., class-level error concentration) or underlying model vulnerabilities (e.g., dataset bias, reliance on spurious features). The entire evaluation is a benchmark of the testing tool, not a diagnostic analysis of the models under test.",
